         <h1>John Alton, 94, Whose Camera Helped Give Form to Film Noir </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>John Alton , whose cinematography helped define film noir and who later shared an Academy Award for '' An American in Paris , '' died on June 2 in Santa Monica , Calif . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 94 and lived in Los Angeles . <br><blue>3</blue>Mr. Alton was born in Sopron , Hungary , and immigrated to America in 1919 . <br><blue>4</blue>After spending four years as a lab technician for Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer , he became a cameraman at Paramount in 1928 , working on films like '' Spoilers of the West '' and '' Wyoming , '' which were produced by David O. Selznick . <br><blue>5</blue>He also did location shooting in Europe for several films , including Ernst Lubitsch 's '' Student Prince . '' <br><blue>6</blue>In the early 1930 's he went to Argentina , where he helped create the country 's first sound stage and directed more than 20 films . <br><blue>7</blue>After returning to Hollywood in the late 1930 's , Mr. Alton worked on many B pictures , often with the director Anthony Mann . <br><blue>8</blue>They included '' He Walked by Night , '' '' Raw Deal , '' '' Hollow Triumph , '' '' Border Incident , '' '' Devil 's Doorway , '' '' Slightly Scarlet '' and '' T-Men . '' <br><blue>9</blue>His stylized , Rembrandt-esque use of light has been credited with helping define the look of film noir . <br><blue>10</blue>He wrote several books on cinematography , notably '' Painting With Light '' ( 1949 ) which was republished last year by the University of California Press . <br><blue>11</blue>Mr. Alton landed more prestigious assignments after working with Vincent Minnelli on '' Father of the Bride '' and '' An American in Paris , '' for which he filmed the ballet sequence and shared an Oscar for color cinematography with Alfred Gilks . <br><blue>12</blue>His later films included '' Father 's Little Dividend , '' '' The Big Combo , '' '' The Brothers Karamazov '' and '' Elmer Gantry . '' <br><blue>13</blue>In 1962 he began work on '' Birdman of Alcatraz '' but was replaced after the original director , Charles Crichton , was replaced by John Frankenheimer . <br><blue>14</blue>It was his last film , and he spent most of the rest of his life in seclusion in Europe and South America . <br><blue>15</blue>When film scholars discovered that he had quietly returned to the United States , he became the subject of tributes at the Telluride Film Festival and the American Museum of the Moving Image . <br><blue>16</blue>He is survived by a sister , Esther , who lives in Israel . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>more than 20 films</m_str> (6_23) 	<m_str>His later films</m_str> (12_1) 	<br><blue>2(3)</blue>: <m_str>Europe</m_str> (14_20) 	<m_str>the country 's</m_str> (6_15) 	<m_str>Europe</m_str> (5_7) 	<br><blue>3(21)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (13_3) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Alton</m_str> (7_11) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (15_6) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_6) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (8_4) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (15_15) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_12) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_3) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_12) 	<m_str>John Alton , whose cinematography helped define film noir and who later shared an Academy Award for '' An American in Paris</m_str> (1_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Alton</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_8) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (11_29) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Alton</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_15) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>His stylized , Rembrandt-esque use of light</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>It</m_str> (14_1) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
